The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into the negative against closing of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the normal daily business.
The Prague Stock Exchange followed the collapse of Monday at the beginning of Tuesday's business, when it fell by another six percentage points.
This time there was the reason for the break-in on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the market's response to the outcome of the US House of Representatives vote, which had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Case of shares in Asia
A dramatic case occurred on Tuesday with shares on the Asian stock exchanges, although the indices were able to compensate for some of the losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange Index lost nearly four percentage points during the business day, but later managed to offset some of the losses, reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which observes the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, decreased by 3.8 percent, and markets were closed in Shanghai.
The shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange declined by 3.6 percent after the index there.
"The timing of the bailout in the US is uncertain and will affect the financial markets worldwide," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its own monetary policy, independent of the Chinese central bank.
Hong Kong interest rates are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt the draft financial support scheme.
Otherwise, it would threaten that other countries would also be affected by the collapse.
A Bloodbath of American Stocks
On Monday, the American House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion Kč) should be spent.
The legislators thus ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
Bush's view is that the plan would regulate the basic causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilise the entire economy.
The American stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the largest decline in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index dropped by almost seven percent, and had recently recorded a similar decline in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was hardly any indication that the draft would not get through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress concedes: US government allows 700 billion dollars to be pumped into banks
The highest representatives of the American Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance to the American financial system.
This is to be voted on at the beginning of next week.
The US legislators achieved a breakthrough in talks about the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance to the US financial system to a size of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns).
However, this does not mean victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they are allowed to publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated at the American Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services, Barney Frank, told the Reuters agency.
In the Senate, different figures suggest that the plan could probably be voted on at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a communication on the adoption of the plan should be the first significant psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
After that, however, there was a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms that could help markets in practice.
Paulson: The Plan Must Be Effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilise the market should look like," said Democrat Nancy Pelosi to Bloomberg.
You said there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with the American finance minister Henry Paulson the night of Sunday to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunge financial firms into serious losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
You have to continue the health plan even further, but I think we are at the target," says Paulson.
A signal for Asia's business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, legislators are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
The aim is to reassure investors against the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision of the Congress could influence the business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not quite clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, nor is there any doubt as to whether negotiations at the last minute could still fail due to a problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the next few days.
The law, however, will still undergo some changes.
The total amount of aid for the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion will be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
Congress, however, can block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program does not fulfil its function, with a further $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush evaluates progress in negotiations positively
The President has a right of veto in this decision, but Congress can overrule his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has remained, based on obtaining finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
American President Bush was also satisfied with the progress made.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said that Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "estimated the two-way effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
The chairman of the banking committee of the Senate Christopher Dodd, the chief negotiator, said that the legislators had agreed on a responsibility for the money programme, the protection of taxpayers against losses, the conclusion of benefits and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the programme and sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
He's to be run by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," says Paulson.
The plan also anticipates help for homeowners who have problems with the repayment of their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages that it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly costs for the debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to the main economist of Patria Finance, David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but implementation will be very difficult.
"And that is because one does not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government will divide the losses among themselves," said Marek this week to the iHNed.cz server.
According to Marek, whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week is not decisive.
"It is much more important for Congressmen to agree to support the plan and to say goodbye as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement on the adoption is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
