The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the ČTÚ Telecommunications Authority, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the recent steps taken by the European Commission in regulating roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How come prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to scold that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák often agrees with this, who in the past had often said that there was no place for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (by the way he would probably find hardly any frequencies).
But there is one more option - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which the traditional mobile phone providers had to react.
Before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the country's five largest provider.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can concentrate on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually make themselves known as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, in the UK, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half of the cost compared to its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good move to rely on a non-cliche target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could take root in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický's press spokesman also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of service provision."
In the Czech Republic there are no chances, the mobile telephone operators say
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," says Jana Studničková, press spokesperson for the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile telephone operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor emerges.
Their interest in starting a virtual mobile phone provider has been demonstrated for a long time by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customers sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in negotiations," said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršeň of Telefónica O2 in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile's spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in a rare way in line with the O2 statement: "So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to continue to build."
And she adds: "There will hardly be a virtual provider on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
We regard this as the best from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, and another would mean more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something is also evidenced by the long back and forth around the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ was at the time when U:fon came into the market from the company T-Mobile.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competition environment of the mobile phone market was also recently strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
It is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately - unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, had a very typical attitude to this whole problem.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile phone provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile phone provider and a virtual provider about renting the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional providers," said Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by representatives of suppliers.
This is more than questionable by an authority representing consumers' interests and, among other things, ensuring that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
But probably the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the three mobile telephone operators are in almost touch with each other, as a result of their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the petrol stations is certainly just chance and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has found no signs of anti-competitive action in this matter, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing from the telecoms regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators will have a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the entry into the market of a virtual provider.
And the mobile phone provider - logically - has a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if this argument is not taken along, it should at least be a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are remarkably similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a quite common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, it has failed to enforce the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know that too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one looks
First of all, the functioning of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partly public.
Normally, they are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile telephone services offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar kind of resale.
"If there are cases that describe you, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will deal with, which may lead to the termination of the cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not get around with those responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, they may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
In fact, profits from the activities of these companies are not negligible to them, and at the same time, unlike actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows for such types of speculation, despite which the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot have it fully as the normal customers of mobile operators."
That alone, however, would have to seem strange to ČTÚ at least.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
Do mobile operators close their eyes to such action, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the provider's statement that they know nothing about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been pointed out several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers resulted in a significant fall in the price of the various services.
Virtually in all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened precisely at these moments, which by no means sought to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators throw themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in skills in these cases is more than favourable.
But let's not throw the shotgun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile market may soon be back in motion.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will at last not be making more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Wo is my home country on the occasion of the Day of Czech Statehood in a ceremony.
The anthem was re-recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo singing, in choir version and in an instrumental version.
The song was written by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had previously told the Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices that are striking and popular for the solo versions.
"From the very beginning, I tried to maintain a clear diction with both of them, and then with the choir, so that you can understand the text well, so that a harmony can be created," says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was performed for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stand Theatre in the originally Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously accepted it.
The first verse of the song then became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
