On Wednesday, Prague transport companies will also be carrying on a chip for the first time
Wednesday, October 1st, 2008, will enter the history of Prague's transport companies as a date when the first passengers will enter a subway, tram or bus, carrying an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
This can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the chip card Opencard.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it displayed on their smart card at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Since yesterday the coupons are also available on the Internet on the websites of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
They buy the coupon via the Internet, which is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, there is also a desk with trained staff at the disposal of travellers, who advises interested parties when buying the Internet and also places the coupon on the map," says the spokesman for the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons at self-service machines on the Opencard, which are installed in some subway vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, remind of ticket devaluers, the passengers have perhaps already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but it should be eighty by the end of the year," adds Opatrný.
The coupon controls a machine instead of the driver
Operation of the vending machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
All you have to do is introduce the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which mainly the inhabitants from municipalities of the Mittelböhmen region enter the capital.
"In trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport, train attendants have reading equipment that allows them to check the validity of coupons by time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organisation. This organisation compiles timetables for Prague transport operators.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's desk.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed in a marked place on the side of the cash register.
Thus, the driver controls the validity of the coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the featured coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal says.
A passenger who does not travel with suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can again go to the self-service vending machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the US
In 1945 the Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This is evident from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish some groups of Sudeten Germans came to the US president in 1945.
This can be seen, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American President not to allow the "Sudetengaus" - which was taken on the basis of the Munich agreement by Hitler - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says a letter signed with the words "People who have the fate of the Sudeten at heart".
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia makes the Sudeten Germans - aware of the Czech national character - suspect that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protection of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are acknowledging a foreign state for us, which is trying to suppress and eliminate minorities and has not contributed anything at all to the victory of the Allies," says the letter.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is supposedly the fear of revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. President doubted the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he initiated a referendum in the Böhmerwaldgau on whether the inhabitants would become part of the U.S. or live under the protective rule of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of post-war history, it does, however, draw a good picture in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses with regard to the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans had at least had to suspect that they would negotiate their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Still others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was employed as a Budweiser German in the Baltic Sea Navy during the war.
When he was captured in British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would pass them," said Chalupa.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected that they would be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
Don't you think - then pay!
An emotional campaign aimed at drivers
Most expensive action for safety on the streets in Czech history.
This is also how the emotional media campaign, which the Ministry of Transport wants to launch on Wednesday, could be characterised.
