"We retain a certain percentage of these territories, but we will have to assign a similarly high percentage (Israeli territory) to the Palestinians because there will be no peace without this," he added.
He admitted that a possible return would also include East Jerusalem.
"The one who wants security in Jerusalem and, above all, doesn't want tractors or bulldozers rolling over his legs as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up part of Jerusalem," Olmert remarked in allusion to two attacks in the city in July, killing several people and hurt dozens of people.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find a "special solution for the Templar and holy and historical places" located in the territory of the Old Town.
"The one who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will have to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
