Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach flees in danger, does that mean that she also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Only how could you verify that they feel the same if they behave in a similar way to us?
For several years, the Internet magazine Edge has published contributions from famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far, where we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and raise questions of feeling or, more generally, of consciousness, we enter impervious terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees or attacks.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in the short-term memory and the execution / control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in the rest of the primates and seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly affect it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be, is likely to differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, his research poses us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that may be more accessible scientifically.
One could examine the processes of consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But with this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick pursued, one is more likely to refer to the neural correlations of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both may be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the emergence of visualization.
What results for the sensations?
I lead them back to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in one of its own activities.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the brain-located defense system (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) proves memory.
From this point of view, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the Cortex, which distinguish primates and, in particular, humans.
Linked to the linguistic nature, subtle gradations of feeling arise, because we can differentiate and categorize states with the help of words and grammar, in order to attribute them to others as well as to ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations emerge from more primitive activities in the body regions of the cortex and brain stem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, concentrates more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-genusal sensations.
In theory, I cannot contradict this, but I think it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fearful in rats and humans is probably the same in both cases: but how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same if they behave similarly?
A cockroach escapes in danger of fear?
In my eyes, mere behavioral likeness cannot yet prove an equal experience.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove that for humans, how did you want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
