The pride and the hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the exuberances of the theme parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, there is a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first entirely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet places, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, the city she describes – and which made her a tourist destination by taking her to the Florida travel guide produced by the federal writer's project during the Depression – is in many ways a place of very special variety.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what's missing."
Even today, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation about racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told," says Hortense Jones, 59, a native of the city and a community member of the city's oldest church.
It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
On the one hand, it is a stronghold of literature and on the other, an example of the black culture - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Naughty as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Beyond the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown and white painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always takes care of, although he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and what-ever-fits with hourly rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville to self - government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty, full of sexual allusions.
She added, "Some people didn't like this."
It is still remembered here that Hurtson was a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembered that when Hurston came to town, she usually did this without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed with pants, in a city that even today is imagining something of her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," said Mr. Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he was rocking in his chair, on a back-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, in which Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville, there was no major memorial, no large-scale public readings.
"I don't think they understood their contribution in the world or their heritage in the least," says Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turnaround came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to set up a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main street of the community.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"During this time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away," said Mr. Franklin.
"There was even once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to force integration by calling its decision against the school council "offending rather than respecting my race."
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was in some ways positive, it weakened the group's cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its young people.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - they hugged their teacher in the morning and hugged his teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri , daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the non-profit group for the protection of the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students stopped coming from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," said Ms. Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped to create room for more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who have ignored prejudices, as they have done, with positive self-confidence and statements such as: "How can anyone refuse the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker set off for Hurston's nameless tomb and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a highly praised Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found in the bookshelves, and made it once again part of the American literature canon.
The road project came at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as their savior.
The municipality began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway revived the city, accelerated it at top speed, aroused real citizen pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city's self-image.
More and more people came, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began re-appreciating the past.
Eatonville was included in the National Historical Register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (of course named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays, Eatonville is still a speciality in Florida: only 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(She's 90% black these days.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its significance are often treated with caution.
For most interviews, permission is necessary in advance and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in field work - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a dark red fondness, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time as the Hurston Festival grew, an increased degree of home pride was born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and muddled like any other race and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to college in Eatonville to work in the city administration or the police, who, according to him, could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who go through only here will think, "Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others," said Alondra Kenon the other day on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at your story for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
