Conversation - Of Blood That Has Been Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
It is known that during the 1980 ' s, national blood reserves administered by the Red Cross's blood donation service were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and to draw up guidelines to prevent another disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to give his report, several provinces set up a committee at that time, whose aim was to develop a new system for managing blood canned blood in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood society to provide for the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood supply system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of the blood cans and through the work in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence,' she says, before proudly emphasizing that at the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
And we didn't have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we were referring to one of the main guidelines of Krever and Gélineau's reports, according to which we are applying exclusion measures if we do not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was taken from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proved that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has quite a meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which allow the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the previously used tests.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not see it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one in every 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV - infected blood.
`In other words, this means that 12 million canned blood must be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 units of blood each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs where HIV was transmitted via a unit of blood.
I think you can feel comfortable these days when you get or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore your health,' says Hema-Quebec's directorate.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted through insects over the blood.
We need to monitor continuously,' continues Dr. Décary, before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide a sufficient supply in addition to a secure supply.
`The demand is rising because the population is ageing.
Since the cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which on average only accounts for 3% of Quebec's population. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is widespread are excluded from blood donation for a year.
`With these 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep it and make it become regular donors.
Life is so hectic nowadays that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,' regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec not only delivers blood canned tissue, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively in serious burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood on stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukaemia.
`A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand annually.
‘We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,' explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
‘Many mothers are convinced that they do not have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
