Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, Vice-Director General of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
It confirms, and follows an orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company sought a slander suit of six million against three authors and a small penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of libel charges, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin everyone who dares to express one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the trial proceeds, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defenses and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics of these unequal struggles are often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the opposite side and also deters anyone who dares to revisit the question.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of things before public opinion.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates are usually held in Canada through the exchange of ideas and not by clubs.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and, at the same time, disregard the views of the public?
Apparently, in the Vice-President's world, this word only includes generously paid lawyers, not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public, which supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, does this mainly because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a gag (in the course of the 'public debate', Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, in which they demand that they no longer use this term...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's complaint is a direct attack on freedom of academic research and the truth-finding that is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to control debates and inconsistencies and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, unlike what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the university world, as well as to the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures that restrict this type of unjustified complaint.
Wall Street Rescue - Democrats and Republicans Understand
The Bush administration and the leading congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the most extensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis, which has been shaking Wall Street for months, still needs to be adopted by the two Congressional Chambers.
The main content is: better control of Members of Parliament on the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money used, new orders to reduce the number of houses seized due to arrears of payment, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the managers of the supported companies.
The American financial secretary Henry Paulson, the president of the Nancy Pelosi Chamber of Deputies, and the Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
'We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective,' said the Bush administration representative, Henry Paulson.
'Everything happened to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,' the Democrat explained.
'This is the fundamental point: if we do not, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily life of Americans will be enormous,' declared Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated during the last two hours, out of fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two US presidential candidates, who only took part late in the negotiations, were more likely to support the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain injunctions to the agreement, especially those that should allow owners to keep their homes, and those that concern the salaries of senior employees of the state-saved companies.
‘If taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain persons, that is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary,' he said on American television stations.
When asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: `I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
'The guiding principles that I have read show that this is one thing that we will all have to digest, and with which we will be able to progress.
The option of doing nothing is simply unacceptable,' he said.
The 700 billion dollar plan is aimed at using taxpayers' money
It comes 14 months after a crisis, triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which initially led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime) before it expanded to other forms of more widespread bonds (PCAA), and finally to a freeze of financial strength and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed last week's first attempt to reach an agreement.
Since the democrats accepted that certain 'toxic' assets of societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not bought, one believes that the dead end will escape.
In order to round off the perspective for everyone in Congress, an order has also been added, which states that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes in order to recover its capital used.
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the President considers it necessary.
