The psychology of outbidding - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was to play lottery, while the other was to participate in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cortex, was measured with losers of the auction, in which the outbidding of the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore felt that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to substantiate their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally carried out investigations to trace the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised $15 reward in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis was on winning one while the other was on losing the other.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "against losing" playing group were willing to play higher stakes than those in the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
They have so far only justified the behaviour observed at auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation ready" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in the case of hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. semen, vaginal secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against the viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against the virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
Thereafter jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B-induced, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only 1 in 10 people are infected with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular control checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more frequently: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected in routine laboratory tests, it is advisable to visit the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in good time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
30 September is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 for the first time by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
Are believers less in pain?
As recent research has shown, religious faith acts like a kind of "pain" that is said to have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: to what extent belief in God influences human feelings of pain, the British paper "Telegraph" reported.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
The results showed that believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
By means of brain-scan technology, it could even be demonstrated that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to concentrate heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would create a kind of religious trance while choosing da Vinci's image because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, receiving a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages during that time, while viewing either the religious or the other painting.
Catholics reported that when they saw the Mother of God, they felt "in safety" as if they were "concerned", and they felt "rest and peace".
While viewing the religious painting, they reported over 12% less pain than when they saw Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that with other strong-acting images one could also cause similar effects with the atheists, one would just have to find the corresponding photo.
"We need to find an image that creates very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practising faith should change our personality, and it does so in many cases," says Wright.
According to these excellent results, only the question remains of what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
