Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said: he wished Google would be able to answer questions such as "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What job really suits me?", but software programs are not yet able to do so, as they don't know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches the search terms are registered, as well as the IP addresses from which they were searched, and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save his own search history and then to use it later so that the hits can be generated much more precisely later, and on the same logic the so-called "recommendations" with which the system recommends tailor-made products and services based on previous preferences.
However, the users wonder what happens in the event of data abuse - "If you look what I do" - some people are concerned about the Google data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is rather the potential power represented by the company that has a terrifying effect, and less the sense of guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or the revolt against the power that many Internet users are opposed to.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties in the event of an event, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was recently the action against pedophilia in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called "Orkut" and also enabled the identification of pedophilia.
However, users concerned about personal rights could still breathe in May when Google, together with the civil rights organization EFF, successfully brought the FBI to justice: therefore, Google cannot be forced to issue information to the FBI on a secret request with any point of the constitution in the future.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, but it has been deprived of the list of individual users or their web and search terms list for two months retrospectively.)
So Google's image remains controversial: those who hate to release their personal data, because they fear the loss of their privacy and privacy by using Google services, scour the company with the indignation due to the conservative companies.
However, the American "geek culture", which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which is market leader thanks to Windows, even if both fight for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require identification codes to its users and provides its services free of charge, making an open, constantly updated source code and program package seem far more attractive, youthful and cool than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks look through the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet in a sharp way - a relationship that has become the focus of particular attention in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
The "Web 2.0" is about nothing but collaboration, i.e. the users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show themselves publicly.
An average teenager can manage his profile on several community portals at the same time - from Facebook via Xanga, can connect it with other services, such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can finally integrate all of this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. Furthermore, they can run blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries that are cast on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove: When looking at last night's party photos, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend has been enjoying himself with, or the employee is dismissed because in his blog he is only too honest about his anger about corporate management - one thing is certain: the term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Those who lead an online life are what they reveal of themselves - in such a way one could formulate the basic idea behind the behaviour of today's youth.
And anyone who tries to keep something secret, or even avoid the Google monopoly, can like to do so - such as with Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine, but deliberately leaves no traces.
Not a few people deliberately do not register on community sites so that they cannot be found, but also the online applications of Google, such as word processing and graphical tools and RSS feeds, can be handled with alternative versions that are not bound to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile of the user.
However, public opinion waits for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), AdWords/AdSense's advertising space threatens the revenues of advertising agencies, and the ever-faster-run services are causing not only Microsoft but other software developers to worry.
Critical viewers, however, also find the disturbing counter-poles: for example, the Corporate Executive Board completely rejected a protest by the employees after the fees of the company's kindergarten were doubled, and the management also said that the multiple meals of the employees were too expensive. However, all this seems almost mild against the fact that Google even fell to the knees before the Chinese government in 2006 and agreed with an agreement that all the dissident hits, or those who violate the good taste, would be filtered out.
The Group's internal regulation is that no new service will be advertised in advance, but only if it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could turn a lot around again: While some think that Google's book and magazine scanning or archiving project is now assuming scale that the company will soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, others are rather concerned about the "Health" system, which allows the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google builds a genetic database already provides the next generation of sci-fi authors with the material - for example "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow describes in best Orwellian manner a future in which a person becomes frighteningly close thanks to Google-related data.
