Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, in which the Nissan engineers were inspired by Hummeln in the creation of new accident-avoiding systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by automotive robots, a mini-car equipped with bees' characteristics, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development, said at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers picked up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If not, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Autorobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect bees' behavior when evading other bees.
And this has to take place in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, do not dodge up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the twistability of the tires.
While there are endless possibilities open to the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotational movement, or the acceleration and braking of the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life span than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to some inputs per second.
It doesn't need to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction based on previous maneuvers, so that it constantly uses only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for megabyte and megabyte memory.
This is the first step in the development of instant collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could be the technology used in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately driving the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
