Napolitano: "Prevention against accidents at work is crucial"
Every day in Italy there are 2500 accidents at work, three people die and 27 remain incapacitated for life.
For the year 2007 the data of the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul Lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These figures prove the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all the provinces of Italy will mark the 58th national day for victims of accidents at work in order to draw the attention of social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm the importance of prevention in the workplace," confirms Pietro Mercandelli, President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano, in his communication to the President of Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del Lavoro).
The Head of State expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to preventing work, protecting injured workers, helping victims' families and raising public opinion".
"A outrageous "basta" has risen up to this, understandable in tragedies that, in terms of their scale, trigger some whirlwinds in the media and public sympathy. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events that can even repeat themselves in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide the fact that "there is, in any case, also a resource problem: there must be a decisive investment in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness of the educational context by young people who are feeding on the world of work are particularly important.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not distract it from its social seriousness. It is necessary to implement and improve a legislative norm.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency that offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not rule out the fact that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," says Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you think you're basically doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents? You can fight it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate the workers who are already starting at school."
"Another effort is needed - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that represents a social emergency is in demand".
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of protection for the victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we have been fighting in recent years".
"The aim is, therefore, to give the worker a guarantee on insurance, so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations, which are decided from time to time by a legislator."
Mp3 player on charges: danger of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which in a report published today in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Csrseri (Scientific Committee on the current and recently identified health risks) of the EU.
"The report states in a note that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music equipment for at least five years per week for more than one hour a day risk the permanent loss of their hearing."
"I am worried that such a large number of young people, who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones on a high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings – that is what the EU says – show a clear risk that pushes too fast to act.
What really matters is to raise consumers' awareness and to make this information a common good.
In view of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology".
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"The scientists - the EU Communication concludes - confirm that there is a good deal of concern and that the European Commission, together with the other EU members and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music equipment and similar equipment".
There is already a European standard which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB.
This damage can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the European Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music devices listen to loud music only five hours a week (in fact, 89 decibels) so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who cross this line risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This would therefore affect 5-10% of users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
