The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already revealed itself a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House's $700 billion savings package: a large part of the Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's New York Times, which reports how the crisis is dividing the Republican party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favoured state institutions and business community, and the neoconservative that is hostile to "the Washington and financial worlds" and wins voters, especially in the south and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example, however, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is announcing or even already represents: not only in the US, but also throughout the West, and perhaps beyond that, will be affected by it.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the long-feared events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis is a decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage a huge amount of the assets of private households living in a single state.
This is an immediate political problem for governments: how to behave towards the affected families, which are also an enormous mass of voters.
So the crisis seems economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism in itself seems to have lost its right to speak: the EU has given clear proof of this, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone is now expecting the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and, above all, distribution of aid funds: since the crisis became increasingly serious, only the US has been in the economic situation to save itself without foreign help.
And in addition to the resources, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that cannot be overvalued – under certain circumstances – which otherwise no international organisation and no market will be able to rely on in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, perfectly in line with the ever greater importance recently attached to a closely related sector in the economy: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now that we have been so convinced that we have long since entered a networked realm, into a realm of ever-different technologies, of the intangible, that we have to realize at once how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to the other in the world, but are still extremely connected to a closely defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in advantage over another who lives in a harvestless, waterless, or oil - free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short boost.
Who says territory, who says government, who says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to generate two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation about the existing leaderships, especially those of economics, which have turned out to be insufficient and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, even more worrying aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of insensitivity, a sense of distance, all directed towards a whole class of managers in the Western countries.
It seems to be the conviction among large sections of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is presented to the majority as ever more foreign and traditional.
The demand for leadership therefore feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of disempowerment of the leading class and the conventional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the sudden change of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, over the collapse of the Labour Party in the UK, towards the rebellion of the American deputies against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value with regard to what is going on in the lower social strata of the West today and is being intensified and driven to over-dimensionality by the financial crisis.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that goes up against walls
Defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and climb up walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which seems to have almost reached its destination.
With an adhesive applied on a surface of only 2.5 qcm, the researchers succeeded in fixing a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American magazine has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure called carbon nanotubes.
"The adhesive principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged into a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang from the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the feet of the reptiles and at the same time "removes them without problems from the wall", says Liming Dai, researcher at the University of Dayton's Faculty of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a perishable adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
For example, to rise on walls like Spiderman? Perhaps, but the researchers think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other fields of application could fall within the space sector.
So for the moment, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH – including the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, Californian scientists present a microfiber adhesive that, like hair, cleans itself from dust by moving on a surface and thus always retains a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in the summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain essential medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of packaged and fresh fruit juices in combination with medication. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again raised the alarm: A glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to the point that they are practically eliminated and thus endanger patients' health.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular medications, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
MEDICATIONS IN DANGEROUS – The same drug agency had warned doctors and patients of the dangers of this mixture in a report two years ago and stressed that they should be careful about what is being drunk in conjunction with medicines such as diazepan or metadon.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal made by Michele Carruba, Director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually passed on immediately to the various international manufacturers who are thus free to change consumer information.
Therefore, it is recommended to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still ambiguities, not to have a pharmacist or doctor to ask you," says Ansa Agency expert.
