Open Office, it appears the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package
The day of OpenOffice.org 3.0's release has come; the Open Source software, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office, gains an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with a few novelties: in addition to a revised and now more spartan designed start menu, a completely guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x is finally achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version, given.
In addition, eight has been added to Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Also interesting are some new features, such as those that allow you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes sending via email easier, for example. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
Thus, "hybrid" PDF files can now be generated, which extend the typical graphics of Adobe format with the elements of a table and a word processing system.
The collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be processed multi-handedly by different users, thus avoiding conflicts in the case of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a Frabe to ensure a better correction procedure.
Some companies are currently publishing various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result will be published in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download on the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request you can send the installation CD to your home or office.
However, if the cost-freeness can be an incentive for the spread of the programme in private households, it is also particularly in the area of business where OpenOffice could succeed the big throw: after all, various institutions of public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the table program, which aims at a displacement of Excel; Impress, for creating presentations as with PowerPoint; Dbase for operating databases instead of the more known Access; and finally Draw, a graphic module.
The goal for 2008 is to achieve 5 million downloads – a goal that can be easily exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
