The housing market for students knows no crises.
According to the last study by the Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 euros in Florence, 650 euros in Naples and 600 euros in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious features. Quite a lot of students lose their right to study, because their families are unable to support them at this level" – according to Sunia's leaders, Laura Mariani – "in these cities, the great demand on the part of the students leads to a deforming of the market, which has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most of the rental offers include a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, no rental price limit, unauthorized sub-rents.
For the Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures which lead to lower rental prices by revising taxation.
If you look at the study, it turns out that in Milan a sleeping place in the Brianza district is needed about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere quarter) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera quarter or even 900 euros in the Vittoria quarter.
In Florence, a sleeping place costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where the students concentrate in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a sleeping place, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping place in a double room.
Only a little lower are the rents in the neighborhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who dodge in outer districts can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a sleeping place, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a sleeping place costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350 euros.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of renting out to non-European students is more common, such as in Perugia, there is even another anomaly: a rent that is 25-30% higher than the average is demanded by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas close due to the favored multiplexkinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the one-room cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the features of a cultural crime.
Most of the time, historical places are full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom you have covered a piece of street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the big prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It's the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these mines paid for the most part the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected are Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are multiplexkinos, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy lists, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but first and foremost there is the preservation of the already existing, because closes a hall in the city, not all of its regular customers are ready to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association out of eight: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros would be needed every year".
It is interesting to note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to its fears about the old cinemas, decided to protect them by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first such agreement in Italy to protect and support the traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be possible to travel to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a gratifying initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also develop new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex rooms, because after all, the audience is more demanding today.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to establish the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid seeing the dusty posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the mafia group Piromalli.
The accusations of the Anti-Mafia Office of Calabria against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of Gioia Tauro municipality, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia business, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the senior mediator between the clan and the public administration, as well as his nephew, was also handcuffed: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the boss of the clan, had already been sentenced for involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at that time to a compensation sum of 10 million euros.
"Disrespectful of any kind of moral and legal standard," the lawyers write, "the two local administrations have decided to pay Piromalli the lawyer money for consulting activities."
"So it was made possible for the mafia group – according to the judges – to enter the town halls in an official way and to co-determine the politics of the public administration."
The President of the Calabrian Regional Committee, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter links between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places where the concentration of the Mafia is greater than in others where such links are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who get a white vest."
This morning's arrests follow those of last July, which, according to the police, was beheaded by the Piromalli clan.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and even then due to alleged links between organised crime and local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the Central-Right Coalition after the May 2006 elections.
He shouted scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He accused Vice-Minniti of inventing everything for political-strategic reasons, but the judges, in connection with the arrest warrant issued this morning, explained that the Piromalli clan had even dared to apply for a change to the A3 project.
From an interception action in connection with the investigations into the Dal Torrione case, the willingness to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – which made the public administration's actions identical to the interests of this clan."
When the energy comes from the waves, suddenly the big ones come up
It is a non-draining source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and only now does this seem to be understood by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and are also looking to occupate, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of gaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; not by chance have these studies intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil came down around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be covered by the ocean waves.
This would be twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides would also be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are relying on marine energy production.
"Chevron investigates these technologies," says the spokesman for a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal, and weighs up the opportunity to work with us."
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a not to be underestimated sign, especially given that oil is still being extracted by the US in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
Technologies that can be improved.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still on the rise, not least because the last doubts have not yet been resolved by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with far greater influence on the environment are needed.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of connected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for the state approval. Part of the energy generated could also be used for military facilities.
However, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a park latz with subsea turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotation movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, a particular interest deserves the potential that is in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is precisely tidal energy that led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
